<subSubSection id="4FF0F1E8FF55FF1FA7ADFE5EFB70DF39" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="0755A263FF55FF1FA7ADFE5EFEF0DDCA" blockId="204.[189,310,433,459]" box="[189,310,433,459]" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">
<heading id="5C1D150FFF55FF1FA7ADFE5EFEF0DDCA" bold="true" box="[189,310,433,459]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" reason="3">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF55FF1FA7ADFE5EFEF0DDCA" bold="true" box="[189,310,433,459]" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0755A263FF55FF1FA7ADFE0FFAD5DE8B" blockId="204.[188,1400,480,651]" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">
Based in part on 
<bibRefCitation id="637BDF92FF55FF1FA690FE0FFD09DDFA" author="Miranda G. S. &amp; Reboleira A. S. P. S." box="[384,719,480,507]" firstAuthor="Miranda" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" pagination="1 - 12" part="820" refId="ref151067" refString="Miranda G. S. &amp; Reboleira A. S. P. S. 2019. Amblypygids of Timor-Leste: First records of the order from the country with the description of a remarkable new species of Sarax (Arachnida, Amblypygi, Charinidae). ZooKeys 820: 1 - 12. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 820.30139" title="Amblypygids of Timor-Leste: First records of the order from the country with the description of a remarkable new species of Sarax (Arachnida, Amblypygi, Charinidae)" type="journal article" year="2019">
<collectingRegion id="C52E6C81FF55FF1FA690FE0FFE25DDFB" box="[384,483,480,506]" country="Venezuela" name="Miranda" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">Miranda</collectingRegion>
&amp; Reboleira (2019)
</bibRefCitation>
, this species may be separated from other species of 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF55FF1FA221FE0EFAB3DDFA" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1892" box="[1329,1397,481,507]" class="Arachnida" family="Charinidae" genus="Sarax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amblypygi" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF55FF1FA221FE0EFAB3DDFA" box="[1329,1397,481,507]" italics="true" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">Sarax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Southeast Asia and Oceania by the following combination of characters: large size (total length 
<quantity id="C0120F86FF55FF1FA224FDEBFF29DE42" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.282" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" unit="mm" value="12.82">12.82 mm</quantity>
); eight anterior setae; only two pairs of lateral eyes; cheliceral claw with six teeth; male gonopod with base of fistula, dorsal lobe and lateral lobe II sclerotized; pedipalp tarsus with two dorsal spines; leg basitibia with four pseudo-articles; leg IV distitibia 
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF55FF1FA40BFD9EFCF5DE8B" box="[795,819,625,650]" italics="true" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">sc</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF55FF1FA47DFD9FFC47DE8B" box="[877,897,624,650]" italics="true" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">sf</emphasis>
series each with six trichobothria.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0755A263FF55FF1FA7ADFD5DFB70DF39" blockId="204.[189,1398,690,825]" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">
The presence of only two pairs of lateral eyes is a unique character state among 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF55FF1FA3FAFD5DFAB5DECD" authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1883" box="[1258,1395,690,716]" class="Arachnida" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amblypygi" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Amblypygi</taxonomicName>
, otherwise known only in a few extinct species, e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF55FF1FA43BFD39FA82DEF0" authority="Wunderlich, 2015" authorityName="Wunderlich" authorityYear="2015" box="[811,1348,726,753]" class="Arachnida" family="Neoamblypygi incertae sedis" genus="Kronocharon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amblypygi" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicalcaris">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF55FF1FA43BFD39FBACDEF1" box="[811,1130,726,752]" italics="true" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">Kronocharon longicalcaris</emphasis>
Wunderlich, 2015
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF55FF1FA7AEFD15FC8BDF15" authority="Engel &amp; Grimaldi, 2014" authorityName="Engel &amp; Grimaldi" authorityYear="2014" box="[190,845,762,788]" class="Arachnida" family="Paracharontidae" genus="Paracharonopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amblypygi" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cambayensis">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF55FF1FA7AEFD15FDE3DF15" box="[190,549,762,788]" italics="true" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">Paracharonopsis cambayensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="637BDF92FF55FF1FA53BFD15FC8BDF15" author="Engel M. S. &amp; Grimaldi D. A." box="[555,845,762,788]" firstAuthor="Engel" journalOrPublisher="Novitates Paleoentomologicae" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" pagination="1 - 17" part="9" refId="ref147976" refString="Engel M. S. &amp; Grimaldi D. A. 2014. Whipspiders (Arachnida: Amblypygi) in amber from the Early Eocene and mid-Cretaceous, including maternal care. Novitates Paleoentomologicae 9: 1 - 17. https: // doi. org / 10.17161 / np. v 0 i 9.4765" title="Whipspiders (Arachnida: Amblypygi) in amber from the Early Eocene and mid-Cretaceous, including maternal care" type="journal article" year="2014">Engel &amp; Grimaldi, 2014</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF55FF1FA449FD15FBD8DF15" authorityName="Miranda &amp; Reboleira" authorityYear="2019" box="[857,1054,762,788]" class="Arachnida" family="Charinidae" genus="Sarax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amblypygi" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="timorensis">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF55FF1FA449FD15FBD8DF15" box="[857,1054,762,788]" italics="true" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">Sarax timorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from these species by its much larger size and the number of spines on the pedipalp. The female is unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4FF0F1E8FF55FF1FA7ADFC8FFBD4DFA8" box="[189,1042,864,938]" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="0755A263FF55FF1FA7ADFC8FFE82DF7B" blockId="204.[189,324,864,890]" box="[189,324,864,890]" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">
<heading id="5C1D150FFF55FF1FA7ADFC8FFE82DF7B" bold="true" box="[189,324,864,890]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" reason="3">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF55FF1FA7ADFC8FFE82DF7B" bold="true" box="[189,324,864,890]" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0755A263FF55FF1FA7ADFC60FBD4DFA8" blockId="204.[189,1042,911,938]" box="[189,1042,911,938]" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">Adjective referring to the island of Timor, on which the species is found.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4FF0F1E8FF55FF1FA7ADFC3DFDB8D862" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="0755A263FF55FF1FA7ADFC3DFE3DDFED" blockId="204.[189,507,977,1004]" box="[189,507,977,1004]" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF55FF1FA7ADFC3DFEABDFEA" bold="true" box="[189,365,977,1004]" pageId="204" pageNumber="205">Type material</emphasis>
(examined)
